"30_date_time.mst — Date/Time. Unusually for this porting effort, most of
 what's MISSING here isn't a MACVM-specific scope cut — it's genuinely
 unimplemented in Strongtalk's own Date.dlt: `julian`, `leapYear:`,
 `daysInMonth:forYear:`, `daysInYear:`, `asSeconds`, and
 `Date class>>julian:` are ALL literally `self unimplemented` in the real
 source (Strongtalk never finished its own Julian-day calendar
 arithmetic). Since `addDays:`/`subtractDays:`/`subtractDate:` all call
 the unimplemented `julian`, they're not ported either — there is no
 working algorithm in the original to port. What IS ported is exactly
 Date.dlt's own working subset: construction from an explicit day/month/
 year, comparison, accessors, weekday/month name lookup, printing.

 `Date class>>today` and `Time class>>now`/`dateAndTimeNow`/`clockValue`
 are still NOT ported — these need a real wall-clock/calendar primitive
 (Windows `SYSTEMTIME` in the original), and MACVM's own internal
 `millisecondClock` (src/runtime/primitives.rs, prim_millisecond_clock)
 is `vm.start_instant.elapsed()`, elapsed time since the VM started — the
 exact same 'not a calendar clock' semantics Strongtalk's own
 `clockValue` doc comment already admits ('elapsed time since Smalltalk
 started'), not a source of wall-clock time either. Calling `today`/`now`
 on these classes is a plain doesNotUnderstand, same as every other
 deliberately-unported method in this whole porting effort (Point's
 Rectangle methods, Bag's `=`, ...) — no stub is added for it.

 `Time class>>millisecondClockValue` IS now implemented (S22) — not a port
 of Strongtalk's own version (which just read Windows' SYSTEMTIME), but a
 real wall-clock primitive built via FFI (docs/FFI.md): milliseconds since
 the Unix epoch, from clock_gettime(CLOCK_REALTIME). See the real Time
 class's own doc comment, right at the definition, for the mmap-scratch-
 buffer/struct-layout mechanics.

 Time.dlt, by contrast, IS fully implemented in the original: it's just
 'seconds since midnight' integer arithmetic (fromSeconds:/hour/minute/
 second/</=/hash/addTime:/subtractTime:/printOn:), and all of it is
 ported faithfully and completely.

 One real fix made while porting, not a straight copy: Date.dlt's own
 `hash` calls `bitXor:` with `self month` (a Symbol) as the argument —
 `((hash bitShift: 4) bitXor: self month) bitXor: hash` — which would
 crash a strict bitXor: primitive expecting an Integer (MACVM's
 SmallInteger>>bitXor: is exactly that). Substituted `monthIndex` (an
 Integer, clearly what was intended for a distribution-mixing hash) —
 the same class of bug-not-feature this whole effort has consistently
 fixed rather than reproduced (e.g. Fraction>>printOn:'s nonexistent
 `stream print:`, Integer>>/'s infinite recursion)."

Object subclass: Date [
    | dayOfMonth monthIndex year |

    Date class >> daysOfWeek [
        ^#(#Monday #Tuesday #Wednesday #Thursday #Friday #Saturday #Sunday)
    ]
    Date class >> monthsOfYear [
        ^#(#January #February #March #April #May #June #July #August
           #September #October #November #December)
    ]
    Date class >> dayOfWeek: dayName [
        ^self daysOfWeek indexOf: dayName ifAbsent: [ self error: 'invalid day name' ]
    ]
    Date class >> indexOfMonth: aName [
        ^self monthsOfYear indexOf: aName ifAbsent: [ self error: 'invalid month name' ]
    ]
    Date class >> nameOfDay: dayIndex [
        ^self daysOfWeek at: dayIndex
    ]
    Date class >> nameOfMonth: index [
        ^self monthsOfYear at: index
    ]
    Date class >> newDay: d monthIndex: m year: y [
        ^self basicNew setDay: d monthIndex: m year: y
    ]
    Date class >> newDay: d month: m year: y [
        ^self newDay: d monthIndex: (self indexOfMonth: m) year: y
    ]
    setDay: d monthIndex: m year: y [
        dayOfMonth := d.
        monthIndex := m.
        year := y.
    ]
    dayOfMonth [
        ^dayOfMonth
    ]
    monthIndex [
        ^monthIndex
    ]
    year [
        ^year
    ]
    month [
        ^Date monthsOfYear at: monthIndex
    ]
    hash [
        | h |
        h := year.
        h := ((h bitShift: 4) bitXor: monthIndex) bitXor: h.
        h := ((h bitShift: 4) bitXor: dayOfMonth) bitXor: h.
        ^h
    ]
    < other [
        ^year < other year
            or: [ year = other year and: [
                monthIndex < other monthIndex
                    or: [ monthIndex = other monthIndex and: [ dayOfMonth < other dayOfMonth ] ] ] ]
    ]
    <= other [
        ^(other < self) not
    ]
    > other [
        ^other < self
    ]
    >= other [
        ^(self < other) not
    ]
    = other [
        (other isKindOf: Date) ifFalse: [ ^false ].
        ^year = other year and: [ monthIndex = other monthIndex and: [ dayOfMonth = other dayOfMonth ] ]
    ]
    printOn: s [
        s nextPutAll: self month.
        s nextPut: $ .
        dayOfMonth printOn: s.
        s nextPutAll: ', '.
        year printOn: s.
    ]
]

Object subclass: Time [
    | seconds |
    <classVars: ClockBuffer>

    Time class >> fromSeconds: s [
        ^self basicNew initSeconds: s
    ]

    "millisecondClockValue — S22, via FFI (docs/FFI.md), filling exactly the
     gap this file's own header comment named: a real wall-clock primitive
     MACVM's internal millisecondClock (elapsed-since-VM-start) never was.
     clock_gettime(CLOCK_REALTIME, &ts) needs a pointer argument, but FFI
     argument marshaling only accepts plain SmallIntegers (src/runtime/
     ffi.rs's marshal_g) — there is no way to pass an Alien object itself as
     an arg. So ClockBuffer holds the ADDRESS (a plain integer) of a 16-byte
     scratch region obtained via a real mmap call (mmap-owned memory is the
     right choice for a buffer handed OUT to native code as a pointer,
     precisely because it's outside the GC heap and can never move mid-call
     — unlike a direct Alien's inline bytes, which live inside a Smalltalk
     object); lazily allocated once and reused forever after.
     struct timespec { long tv_sec; long tv_nsec; } is 16 bytes, both
     fields plain 8-byte longs at offsets 0/8 — confirmed by compiling and
     running a real C probe against this machine's headers (not assumed),
     which is also why clock_gettime was chosen over gettimeofday's
     struct timeval: timeval's tv_usec is a 4-byte int, needing an accessor
     width Alien doesn't expose; timespec maps directly onto the existing
     signedLongAt: accessor with no width mismatch at all."
    Time class >> ffiMmapAddr: a1 length: a2 prot: a3 flags: a4 fd: a5 offset: a6 [
        <primitive: FFI function: #mmap ret: #g args: #(g g g g g g)>
    ]
    Time class >> ffiClockGettime: clockId timespec: addr [
        <primitive: FFI function: #clock_gettime ret: #g args: #(g g)>
    ]
    Time class >> clockBufferAddress [
        ClockBuffer isNil ifTrue: [
            "PROT_READ|PROT_WRITE=3, MAP_PRIVATE|MAP_ANON=4098 (0x1002) —
             real macOS/arm64 flag values, same as world/tests/
             30_ffi_alien_tests.mst's own proven mmap capstone call."
            ClockBuffer := self ffiMmapAddr: 0 length: 16 prot: 3 flags: 4098 fd: -1 offset: 0.
        ].
        ^ClockBuffer
    ]
    "Milliseconds since the Unix epoch (CLOCK_REALTIME=0) — real wall-clock
     time, not elapsed-since-VM-start. Verified live: two calls a few
     milliseconds apart return distinct, correctly-ordered values."
    Time class >> millisecondClockValue [
        | addr ts sec nsec |
        addr := self clockBufferAddress.
        self ffiClockGettime: 0 timespec: addr.
        ts := Alien forAddress: addr size: 16.
        sec := ts signedLongAt: 1.
        nsec := ts signedLongAt: 9.
        ^(sec * 1000) + (nsec // 1000000)
    ]
    initSeconds: s [
        seconds := s.
    ]
    asSeconds [
        ^seconds
    ]
    hour [
        ^seconds // 3600
    ]
    minute [
        ^(seconds \\ 3600) // 60
    ]
    minutes [
        ^seconds // 60
    ]
    second [
        ^seconds \\ 60
    ]
    hash [
        ^seconds hash
    ]
    < other [
        ^seconds < other asSeconds
    ]
    <= other [
        ^(other < self) not
    ]
    > other [
        ^other < self
    ]
    >= other [
        ^(self < other) not
    ]
    = other [
        (other isKindOf: Time) ifFalse: [ ^false ].
        ^seconds = other asSeconds
    ]
    addTime: amt [
        ^Time fromSeconds: seconds + amt asSeconds
    ]
    subtractTime: amt [
        ^Time fromSeconds: seconds - amt asSeconds
    ]
    printOn: s [
        self hour printOn: s.
        s nextPut: $:.
        self minute printOn: s.
        s nextPut: $:.
        self second printOn: s.
    ]
]
